Business support is vital for companies survival and growth. The proposed funding aims to 
(1) address the under provision of support across regions and sectors;
(2) increase business and networking skills and promote knowledge sharing via an online growth platform;
(3) promote the UK tech sector via 5 reports and further insights

One year funding extension to Tech Nation as a transitional arrangement whilst DCMS is launching a grant competition in June 2022 for this funding to be competed for the following two financial years (FY23/24, FY24/25).

The National Wildlife Crime Unit (NWCU) is a police-led specialist unit devoted to tackling or disrupting national and international wildlife crime.
The project contributes to the prevention and detection of wildlife crime both in the United Kingdom
(UK) and internationally by;
a) maintaining a strategic overview of wildlife crime in the UK and making recommendations for wildlife crime priorities for the UK; b) supporting work to tackle the wildlife crime priorities;

c) continuing to support enforcement officers in tackling wildlife crime professionally;

d) contributing to the National Crime Agency national tasking process as required through its membership of the Acquisitive Crime Threat Board.

The Fisheries and Seafood Scheme provides financial assistance for projects that support the development of the catching, processing and aquaculture sectors, and for projects that enhance the marine environment. The scheme is available to applicants whose organisation and/or vessels are registered in England.

The scheme will provide funding for a range of projects that deliver the following high-level outcomes:

Creating a more sustainable and resilient sector;

Boosting the demand for English seafood and accessing new markets;

Improving participation through co-design and co-management;

Achieving good environmental status through the conservation and restoration of the marine environment;

Supporting net zero through reducing emissions within the industry

New areas of the scheme will be opened for applications for a defined period of time through funding rounds. The dates of these funding rounds will be announced in due course.

In the wake of the 12 August shootings in Keyham, Plymouth City Council including Devon & Cornwall Police, with local partners, submitted a five-year "Keyham Recovery Plan" requesting funding from central government for a range of measures under three pillars to rebuild the local community: Health and Wellbeing, Community Safety and Resilience & Legacy. Under the Community Safety pillar, a key element is a bid for target hardening measures, which also includes environemntal improvements and community enagagement. This activity is basis of the grant: 'Plymouth Community Safety - Target Hardening'.

Funding activity similar to that of the Safer Streets Fund, the grant is intended to:
-prevent an increase in neighbourhood crime & anti-social behaviour (i.e. reduce crime);
-stregthen the community;
-improve public perceptions of safety.

The funding would be adminstered by the Police and Crime Commissioner of Devon & Cornwall, in parternship with local partners such as the city council, local police force and the local community.

The purpose of the proposed funding is to support the NSPAs crucial role in the suicide prevention landscape allowing the NSPA to: 
 foster greater collaboration across sectors to drive change;
 share information, good practice and resources - building both capacity and knowledge; 
 provide a collective voice to inform national and local policy and practice; 
 further grow and diversify the Alliances membership;
 Support the NSPAs Lived Experience Network, which was set up in 2020, and enable the NSPA to provide insights to DHSC from that Network to support policy development.

adaptation data and indicators, with focus on those comparable to UK sectors. It will set momentum for further collaboration at international level;

2) Aim to provide policy guidance on using data and indicators to track progress towards adaptation;

3) Build monitoring systems and data sets, at international, national and subnational levels, in selected countries, including the UK.

This grant would go largely towards step 1 of the OECD work on climate adaptation metrics and indicators with the output being a draft report of the state of play in this space with a review of international literature and two workshops.

Environmental Stewardship is an agri-environment scheme helping to:
Improve water quality and reduce soil erosion  by encouraging management which can help to meet these aims;
Improve conditions for farmland wildlife  including birds, mammals, butterflies and bees;
Maintain and enhance landscape character  by helping to maintain important features such as traditional field boundaries;
Protect the historic environment  including archaeological features and artefacts.
The scheme, which replaces the older Countryside Stewardship and Environmentally Sensitive Area schemes, is composed of two levels: the Entry Level Stewardship (ELS), Organic Entry Level Stewardship (OELS) for Organic farms, Upland Entry Level Stewardship (UELS) comprising the lower levels; and the Higher Level Stewardship (HLS) for the upper level.

This is a demand-led programme budget, made up of budgets as follows: Funding for Exceptional costs (EAG), Admissions Appeals, Short Term Cash Advances and Recoveries.
Exceptional costs funding is considered where funding is for costs that are not met by other budgets i.e., TUPE or Deficit Funding;
Reimbursement of Admissions Appeals for costs incurred by academies over and above 20 appeals;
Short term advances for short term cash flow issues (repayable within 12 months);
Requests for funding against this budget are subject to business cases.

To facilitate the merger of Kensington and Chelsea College into Morley College to: 
 enable financial sustainability of the college by June 2025 without a requirement for Government funding to support operating losses;
 secure good quality provision;
 provide learning opportunities that respond to the needs of learners and employers in the area served by the merged college; and
