To address drug-related deaths and crime by taking a whole-system and whole-of-Government approach, ADDER (Addiction Diversion Disruption Enforcement and Recovery) Place-based Accelerators will integrate and coordinate place-based enforcement, diversionary, treatment and recovery (including housing and employment) programmes in five new areas of England. The funding will enable local areas to build on existing work and look to expand multi-agency partnership working in the local areas to drive sustained health- and crime-related outcomes; and help to inform the evidence base for future Government intervention and national investment in this field.

Over a period of two years, the project will aim to start to deliver reductions in: 
 the rate of drug-related deaths;  
 drug-related offending; 
 prevalence of drug use.
ADDER accelerator areas will realise the programme aims by working together to achieve the following outcomes:
 Reduced likelihood of drug-related deaths;
 A reduction in drug related reoffending amongst prolific offenders within local areas;
 Increase in the numbers of drug users engaging in treatment as well as increases in those achieving and sustaining recovery;
 Increase in the number of people moving into paid employment from drug treatment services; 
 A reduction in drug supply within pilot areas;
 Reduced costs for local health services and police forces due to lower health and crime harms, and lower costs to the criminal justice system (as fewer people are dealt with by the courts);
 Increase in number of young and vulnerable people safeguarded.
This would be delivered through the following outputs:   
 Developing a whole-system approach between enforcement, treatment and local authority partners within your local area 
 Enhanced co-ordinated law enforcement activity targeting drug dealers and users.
 Increased use of diversionary interventions to use the criminal justice system to divert users away from offending
 Enhanced treatment and recovery service provision.

DHSC core funding to the AMS underpin the delivery of Government R&D priorities by:
Supporting excellent research and outstanding researchers;
­Developing research links and collaborations with the best overseas researchers;
­Utilising the knowledge and experience of AMS Fellows, and well-established UK and international networks, to ensure UK research is used to support overseas development;
­Providing authoritative and independent advice that contributes to the evidence base for public policy-making;
­Supporting activities that help to increase the size and diversity of the research workforce; and,
­Encouraging public engagement in science and engineering issues.

Grant funding to the National Park Authorities to support the delivery of their statutory purposes to:
Conserve and enhance natural beauty, wildlife and cultural heritage (Conservation);
Promote opportunities for the understanding and enjoyment of the special qualities of National Parks by the public (Recreation).

Increase the quality and quantity of nurse training places in countries leading to an increase of better trained nurses;
Deliver training that leads to nurse qualifications to refugees/displaced people; 
Support governments to improve their health workforce management; and
Develop strong partnerships between local health systems and the NHS

Aims:
Build and strengthen the evidence base on what works to improve the educational outcomes of children in need;
Test effective methods of strengthening the relationships between children's social care and schools;
Improve our understanding of the impacts of strengthening key support roles in schools and social care for improving outcomes for children in need;
Continue to establish a culture of evidence-based practice in the children's social care sector and help schools and social care understand what works to improve outcomes for children in need;
Give the sector what it needs to shape practice and provide support for children in need, e.g. by resourcing professionals (including social workers, teachers, and others) working with children in need;
Objectives:
Test the effectiveness of embedding social workers in schools;
Gain evidence-based feedback on whether and how supervision would be an effective support mechanism for us to build into the strengthened DSL role;
Test the impact of four Signs of Potential interventions at a larger scale and develop and conduct initial research on two or more new interventions that specifically target supporting young people with social care experience to thrive and succeed in education;
Share findings from all four projects widely among the education and social care sectors and find ways of influencing the take up of new ideas/initiatives.

WWCSC shall use all reasonable endeavours to achieve the following aims:
Identify gaps in evidence, and create new evidence through trials and evaluations;
Collate, synthesise, and review existing evidence;
Develop, test, and publish tools and services that support the greater use of evidence;
Champion the application of robust standards, and appropriate dissemination of evidence in children's social care research.
